description:
Inyo Mountains parsley, Lomatium foeniculaceum ssp. inyoense, White Mountains, elevation 3045 m (9990 ft).

Seems consistently separated ecologically and morphologically from other varieties of L. foeniculaceum, and maintains uniform phenotype in the White Mountains and eastern California.  The disjunct reports from northeastern Nevada and southern Idaho may or may not be as distinct, but almost certainly are not part of the same biological entity.

description:
King bladderpod, Physaria kingii ssp. kingii, White Mountains, elevation 3000 m (9850 ft).

One of two color forms in the White Mountains, this cream colored variant found in sandy and gravelly soils derived mainly from siliceous rock (granite, sandstone) in the Crooked Creek drainage, and was also seen in 1987 at 12420 ft elevation northeast of White Mountain Peak.  The form with bright yellow flowers is more widely distributed in the White Mountains, usually on carbonate substrates.  The two forms seem to maintain distinct populations, but apparently are otherwise indistinguishable.

description:
Growing at the base of Dogwood (Cornus) tree, possiby C. nuttallii in a concrete planter near staircases on the South side of the Earth and Marine Sciences (EMS) Building.

Flesh white, negative in KOH.
Flesh and pore surface staining pinkish when cut or bruised, becoming reddish brown later.
Fresh growing edge with a pinkish-reddish band when moist (not visible here).
Hymenium mostly poroid, but also lamellate to somewhat dentate, walls relatively thin and close.
Texture leathery, but pliable and compressible like fresh Turkey Tails, although thicker.
Surface very soft and very finely velutinous (not visible without hand lens).

Capitate hyphal ends in hymenium present.
Dimitic hyphal system? – Skeletal hyphae definitely present.
Spores long-ellipsoid, with very indistinct but visible apiculus. 5.7 × 3.8 microns. Q=1.5. I think this rules out Dadaeleopsis, which is where I would have placed it.

Taste mild, odor like fresh turkey tails (fungal).

This is another one of things that are pretty common to seasoned divers but pretty awesome to me.  Can you believe they're hydroids?!

One of the fun things about being a relatively inexperienced diver is the common things are totally awesome. I haven't been to the famous Metridium Fields at Monterey, and I've never seen these giant Metridium before, so I was pretty psyched to see them growing all over the anchor! As you can see, there was a bit too much chunk to get a decent shot of things this big (each was about the size of my thigh), but whatever. They were spectacular.

Those white things are the feeding tentacles of a spaghetti worm.  The pink banded fuzzy looking things are the arms of brittle stars, and there are some strawberry anemones thrown in there too.  All pretty common, but it's still a treat to look down and see this.  Not all dive sites are this rich!

description: You don't have to put on a silly suit, breath through a tube, and fall through 100 ft of water to see scenes like this, and yet I did!

The only other time I've seen this slug was on another dive, also with Brenna and John Yasaki.  Brenna pointed one out to me but I was too cold to care.  Note that "too cold to care about slug" equates to early onset hypothermia for me.  This time, though, I felt wonderful, found a bunch on my own, and managed to stay still enough to get a picture.  Yay!

When you learn about sea slugs in California, the Spanish Shawl usually comes up as an example of how insanely colorful they can be, and yet they're fairly rare in the intertidal around the Bay Area.  I've longed to see one for some time, but have never struck gold (amethyst?).  Luckily, I got to tag along with Brenna and John to Anchor #1, a dive site about a mile off shore of the Breakwater at Monterey, where they are common.  Sure enough, there they were, in all their garish, long-tentacled glory!
Lacy bryozoans, one more common thing I rarely get to see, except while diving.
